State MSM Profile: Iowa

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Iowa

An estimated 20,752 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Iowa in 2013, representing 0.5% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 1,145,708 adult men of Iowa, 1.8% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Iowa resided in counties within medium or small metropolitan areas (66.0%). No MSM in Iowa resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Iowa, 2013

MSM in Iowa Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Iowa, Polk County had the largest population of MSM at 4,044, representing 19.5% of all MSM in the state. Washington County had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Iowa at 5.2%. This was greater than the percentage for Iowa as a whole, which was 1.8% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Iowa Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Des Moines-West Des Moines Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Des Moines-West Des Moines MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Iowa at 4,872, or 23.5% of all MSM in the state. Of the 208,392 adult men in Des Moines-West Des Moines, an estimated 2.3% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Cedar Rapids Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Cedar Rapids MSA had a population of 1,889 MSM, or 9.1% of all MSM in Iowa. Of the 96,804 adult men in Cedar Rapids, an estimated 2.0% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Iowa City Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Iowa City MSA had a population of 1,376 MSM, or 6.6% of all MSM in Iowa. Of the 61,192 adult men in Iowa City, an estimated 2.2% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Davenport-Moline-Rock Island Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Davenport-Moline-Rock Island MSA overlaps two states: Illinois and Iowa. The Iowa portion of the MSA had 1,234 MSM, or 5.9% of all MSM in the state and 42.0% of the 2,939 MSM in the MSA. Of 61,095 adult men in the Iowa part of Davenport-Moline-Rock Island, 2.0% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 2.1% of adult men (2,939 out of 141,506).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Waterloo-Cedar Falls Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Waterloo-Cedar Falls MSA had a population of 1,178 MSM, or 5.7% of all MSM in Iowa. Of the 63,477 adult men in Waterloo-Cedar Falls, an estimated 1.9% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Omaha-Council Bluffs Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Omaha-Council Bluffs MSA overlaps two states: Iowa and Nebraska. The Iowa portion of the MSA had 1,157 MSM, or 5.6% of all MSM in the state and 14.5% of the 7,971 MSM in the MSA. Of 45,220 adult men in the Iowa part of Omaha-Council Bluffs, 2.6% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 2.5% of adult men (7,971 out of 315,494).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Ames Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Ames MSA had a population of 842 MSM, or 4.1% of all MSM in Iowa. Of the 38,785 adult men in Ames, an estimated 2.2% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Sioux City Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Sioux City MSA overlaps three states: Iowa, Nebraska and South Dakota. The Iowa portion of the MSA had 608 MSM, or 2.9% of all MSM in the state and 62.9% of the 967 MSM in the MSA. Of 45,721 adult men in the Iowa part of Sioux City, 1.3% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 1.6% of adult men (967 out of 60,459).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Dubuque Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Dubuque MSA had a population of 543 MSM, or 2.6% of all MSM in Iowa. Of the 35,260 adult men in Dubuque, an estimated 1.5% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
